<font color="#FF0000">KALI TAL</font><br>
<tt>Thu Apr 17  6:47:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I think that this Kali Tal thing is pretty much overblown.<br><br>
Doc Spatz posted a message from her that had been intended to be private e mail. Was she aware that the message was to be read by visitors to this site? I seriously doubt Kali Tal will be visiting this site anytime soon. So, Doc, lighten up.<br><br>
I have visited the Sixties Project site several times over the past year and really don't have much of an opinion about it.<br><br>
As a veteran, I am very secure insofar as my role in providing information concerning the Vietnam War.<br><br>
I don't feel threatened by the remnants of the Anti War Movement nor its perceived effort to &quot;rewrite history&quot;. If there is a movement by either the left or the right to *channel* public opinion into their respective camps, I have faith that modern day students have enough brains to &quot;smell a rat&quot;. <br><br>
Today's students are detached from the events that occurred during the Sixties because they weren't alive then. They are much less likely to write reports or essays with agendas that require justification or slanting. <br><br>
I have faith that students of today want BOTH sides of any issue.<br><br>
Kali Tal's site may not cater to Vietnam Vets, so what? <br><br>
We, who served, are the real authorities of American participation in Vietnam. This is &quot;driven home&quot; each time a college or high school kid sends me a message that inquires, &quot;What was it like?&quot; <br><br>
Our experience was only a *part* of those times, though.<br><br>
Let's NOT forget the Vietnamese!<br><br>
To be sure, every person who lived in the 1960's has something important to say about those times - even those who were indifferent. <br><br>
Many people were a few years beyond the draft. They were caught up in their personal lives, and were busy raising families. They didn't have opinions about the war. Shouldn't this also be understood? <br><br>
Each story is important. <br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@green.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


